    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-11-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-11-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="236"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d236">
                <head>236. Memorandum Prepared by <persName>John S.D. Eisenhower</persName>,
                    Assistant White House Staff Secretary<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d236fn1"
                        >Source: Eisenhower Library, Whitman File, <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Diaries. Extract. Top Secret. Omitted are brief
                        unrelated items reporting on developments in Laos, Iraq, France/Algeria,
                        Turkey, and Guatemala.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1960-11-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 14, 1960</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3. <hi rend="italic">South Vietnam</hi>—Suppression of the attempted coup against
                    President <persName corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName> appeared virtually
                    complete by the afternoon of 12 November with the surrender of nearly all rebel
                    paratroopers to loyal forces which had entered Saigon in response to <persName
                        corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName>’s earlier radio appeals. Efforts are
                    being made to stabilize the military situation as rapidly as possible in order
                    to prevent Communist guerrillas from profiting by the diversion of field units
                    to Saigon. Some increase in Communist activity has been reported in Tay Ninh
                    Province west of Saigon.</p>
                <p>Our Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DE1">Durbrow</persName> has urged <persName
                        corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName> not to take severe retaliatory measures
                    and has urged that he take stock of his family’s participation in government.
                    While he applauds Diem’s fortitude in this crisis, and while he admits there is
                    no weakening of anti-Communist sentiment, he still points out that the existence
                    of this uprising is harmful to <persName corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName>’s
                    standing and indicates considerable dissatisfaction within elements of the
                    country.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">John S.D. Eisenhower</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
